rComments: I didn't take this course seriously when I signed up. For a good part of the first lecture, I honestly thought to myself "great, we're going to have to sit through 12 weeks of some middle aged guy showing us his Facebook feed." I've never been more wrong. You'll never look at a screen or any media the same way again.

2 essay assignment, and multiple choice midterm and final. Essay pretty easy since its not research essay, but multiple choice questions are too hard. If it is an online exam, must do with a group. Lectures a must but boring voice, content gets interesting when he uses a lot of video's.

Dunno if he teaches this class anymore, but Professor Petit was hilarious. Don't ever miss his lectures as he explains the concepts really clearly and you won't ever be bored. He does assign a ton of readings, moreso than other psych classes. Make sure to take lecture notes + read the textbook to do well.
thought this class would be fun, but the lectures are TOO BORING!
Very clear and well structured class.
sooo hard... so very hard...

Extremely funny professor. Used many interesting scenarios and examples to explain concepts. Attend all lectures because he teaches things that are not mentioned in the textbook and he doesn't use lecture slides. And make sure you read the textbook. A little effort, but getting an A is possible.

Professor Petit is SO funny! A very entertaining and enjoyable class, with extremely useful material. Exams are not exactly easy,  but they are fair. Yes there are 8 chapters on each exam but the book is small in comparison to other text books.

The key to success in this class is taking notes while in class (he doesn't use lecture slides) and to keep up with the textbook (lectures and text don't overlap).  If you do both of those things, it's a guaranteed 4.0, exams aren't as hard as everyone says.

Good explanations, interesting lectures, good material but ridiculous use of the textbook (soo much to read and so lengthy) also examss were so hard like impeccably difficult, i had a 4.0 in 2nd year till this course

This prof was hilarious. He has a bit of a twisted humor though. He's very easy going but his lectures do not consist of slides (unless its to show pictures). His exams were fair. But to do well, you have to read the textbook and attend/pay attention to lectures. Textbook and lectures were both interesting though

He explains everything very clearly and is a very relaxed lecturer. The textbook is used EXTENSIVLY! More than average amount a readings per week. You need to memorize a lot of fine details and need to put aside a lot of study time

They funniest professor I've ever had (in the 30 courses that I've taken so far). His humor may seem gross to some but I loved it. For the Neuro students, the course shouldn't be hard but for the psychology students, be careful, this is NOT what you're used to!
Took his class online, and he was able to keep me from browsing other sites. Textbook is brutal to read, but a necessary evil. Keep all your notes as exams are cumulative.
explains in great details.

Amazing prof. I liked the way he explains the concepts--crystal clear!! For all of u who thinks his exams are a killer, you should see the anatomy exams. These exams are much harder than Petit's. The textbook is not hard! They're much better than reading the journal articles in the upper yr psych courses, e.g., advanced personality psych readings.

Great prof. People say that his exams are hard but if u read the textbook and attend lectures, it's easy. Nothing is a surprise in his class. His lecture material on the exam is easy. The textbook material is alright. If you are a psych student taking this class u may find it a bit challenging, but if you're a neuroscience student it's all old news

His lectures are very entertaining, but his exams are brutal and unfair. The textbook is challenging at times, and you are kind of on your own since he doesn't go over it during lectures. I wouldn't recommend taking this course unless its a program requirement.

Petit's lectures are very fun, and hes really funny too. General guideline: if you want to do well in this class take detailed lecture notes (study them), and detailed textbook notes (study those). keep up with the material and youll be fine. all his questions are "which of the following are false" haha

The material is interesting to read. Lectures can be hard to follow if you haven't read the book beforehand. The exams are impossible to do unless you have photographic memory. I can't believe the extent in which Broca's numbers were tested. I would say this course is more about memorizing than understanding. "Which one is false?" Qs drove me nuts!

Extremely interesting course, ruined by Petit. He explains things well but the exams are unfair. I lived this class and still ended up with an average mark. If he spent more time helping rather than talking about his arm and medication he is on, I'm sure more people would have done better. Was RUDE when i went for help!!!!! exam ruins gpa!!!

Prof. Ted Petit is an amazing lecturer and the course itself is amazing. When you read the text book in conjunction with his lectures, it all just comes together. Pretty soon, you'll be wishing you wanted to become a neuropsychologist yourself. Love it. The midterm is easy but the final... is something else. Work hard though, truly it will pay off.

Very difficult exams.  Prof explains things clearly but focuses too long on simple things and then brushes over complicated items with a "but you already know this...".  Higher than average reading load from textbook.
Amazing prof, makes the hardest things sound so simple. His exams are KILLER.
great prof, agreed? =)

Great lecturer! Very clear and gives lots of examples. The bad part is that he sometimes says medical terms very quickly and doesn't mention the spelling. Very interesting course worth taking.  Exams are challenging but fair if you study; there's no surpise q's. Rep as being hard couse but it's nowhere as diffucult as the neuro ones.

Here is the thing with Petit, His lectures are pretty amazing, I mean the guy knows in and out about what he is talking about. He clearly explains the concepts about NeuroPsycholgy, Being the fact that Neuropsy being an interesting course I think he made the course even interesting and outstanding.His midterm/exams follows the same format 50MCQS
i agree with the overall assesment great prof, interesting lecture, but the textbook is to wordy, and exam are killer, you've been warned.

Great and awesome professor. Interesting and informative lectures. Difficult textbook. Horrible exams! Although you can probably do well if you're a good guesser or if you have enough memory in your brain to memorize the whole textbook and lectures in great DETAIL! This is probably the toughest 2nd year course I've ever taken.
Interesting class, great prof, horrible textbook.
Don't take this class if it is not ur requirement

I was really scared about taking this class, as I'd heard horrible things about it (well more specifically, it's exams!!) However, if you devote a lot of time to it, you CAN do well. Though the textbook is cumbersome to get through, once I got into it I found myself interested in the material. It doesn't hurt that Prof. Petit is a great lecturer!!
Great prof. Class material is interesting but textbook is boring, long and wordy. Exam format is death, horrible exams... *shudder*
He is a GREAT prof. Very funny. The course is ineteresting but hard and the textbook is a killer.
Interesting course! Enjoyable experience with Prof. Petit. BUT pleaaaase get rid of the textbook, it's HORRIBLE! It can literally put me to sleep, seriously!
Great lectures, tough class. Text book is DRY!
He's hilarious.

great prof., good personality. Very clear in lectures - repeats things and says them slowly, spells them out for you, draws diagrams, asks the class if they understand. Very lively, interesting. Text is incredibly difficult to go through and remember. Exams are fair but hard if you don't study well.

Great prof.  Lectures were facinating and very insightful.  Unfortunately, the textbook was really hard to work through, and the exams were absolutely brutal.  I enjoyed the course, but unfortunately the outcome of the exams ruined it for me.  Brace yourself if taking this course, you better have a great memory!
the guy knows how to explain all those neuro-bio-brain things very clearly...which fact helps A LOT!!!!!

Without doubt the most interesting class. Lectures are clear and concise, and he adequately purveys course material. The textbook, on the other hand, is incredibly difficult to work through. Well written, but there is alot of material in teh text that could easily be testable. My midterm resulted in 110 pages of notes that I had to go over!

Petit is a great prof, lectures are very interesting and he makes the material understandable. The exams were hard and very specific from the book but overall this course is really good. They should change the textbook for this class.
Yea, eh, Hard clas.. Don't take et

just had final...god...even worse than midterm....again, everything was 'which of the following is false?', which are insanely hard. overall, i would say this is by far the HARDEST and most DEMANDING 2nd year psychology course utsc has to offer.workload is far far far above average.

Mid term was hard, entire thing was 'which is false' which I guess was how he managed to cram 9 chapters & all those lectures in. But the course is interesting and the lectures are good. Lecture questions were easier than the text ones which were very specific.

omg i just wrote my midterm yesterday..it was HORRIBLE....all the questions were 'which of the following is false?' format, and he based his questions on tiny facts from the book...i swear he probably focused on like two sentences from each chapter.....how ridiculous- 9 chapters for 1 midterm...n only abt 25 questions from all that reading.

Yes, lectures are interesting, but he doesn't go over 25% of textbook material (which we will be tested on). Also, reading is v. hard, and we have to memorize minute facts of the brain, and there's only a couple questions per chapter of the textbook, and NINE LONG CHAPTERS on the midterm. Very unreasonable!!!!!

I agree he is very unfair...exams are ridiculous...9 long chapters and only 2 questions per chapter on exam...ridiculous...gives you no incentive to study since most of the stuff in the book wont be on exam, not the nicest guy either but seems smart.
This prof is incredibly unfair and the textbook is horrible.
Great prof, really wants his students to do well, exams are easy as long as you read the textbook. Lectures are interesting, as is the course material.
No Comments
He is not available for help, but otherwise cool and his exams are pretty easy
good instructor, exam is not that hard, just read material and youll be fine
Not available to help, hard exams but good lecturer. Can cover more from book
very hard exams, half of exam on lec. half on book, book half is impossible!!!
No Comments
Lectures amusing and informative, exam is hard
tries to entertain - not available for questions
